    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-10T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-10T02:00:00-05:00" n="138"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">780.5/6–1053: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 138<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey (<persName type="from"
                            >McGhee</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-10T09:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 10, 1953—9 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1479. During informal conversation after Foreign Minister’s dinner June 8 for
                    General <persName corresp="#p_RGMB1">Ridgway</persName>, Prime Minister held
                    forth at some length on question <gloss target="#t_ME1">ME</gloss> defense.
                    Prime Minister said that he had read most carefully address of Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF2">Dulles</persName> made June and noted that
                    Secretary considered it necessary delay creation <gloss target="#t_MEDO1"
                        >MEDO</gloss> until Arab States more amenable. He thereupon repeated Turk
                    “setting up shop” theory expressed in Foreign Office memo June 1 (reference
                        <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 1454 June 2 and <gloss
                        target="#t_Embdesp1">Embdesp</gloss> 791 June 3)<note n="1" xml:id="d138fn1"
                        >Neither printed, but see <ref target="#d141fn2">footnotes 2</ref> and <ref
                            target="#d141fn3">3, Document 141</ref>.</note> emphasizing that US, UK,
                    France and Turkey should proceed immediately toward setting up formal <gloss
                        target="#t_MEDO1">MEDO</gloss> in hope that after it was going concern Arab
                    States would desire participate.</p>
                <p>Prime Minister asked why Secretary had lauded General <persName corresp="#p_NGM1"
                        >Naguib</persName>, who is quoted as saying that Malenkov was peace-loving
                    man (see <gloss target="#t_Embdesp1">Embdesp</gloss> 776 May 28 enclosure
                        2,<note n="2" xml:id="d138fn2">Neither printed. (611.82/5–2853)</note>
                    reporting Secretary’s conversation with President). Prime Minister expressed
                    doubt that international interest in Suez and Egyptian sovereignty were, as
                    Secretary indicated, not irreconcilable. Prime Minister stated in light vein,
                    but apparently meaning it, that if British are forced withdraw their troops from
                    Egypt Turks would be glad have them stationed in Turkey.</p>
                <p>Prime Minister mentioned conversation which he had with <persName
                        corresp="#p_ASN1">Nuri Said</persName> in London, in course which he had
                    asked <persName corresp="#p_ASN1">Nuri</persName> whether Iraq could break with
                    Arab League and join with Turkey in creating nucleus for <gloss target="#t_ME1"
                        >ME</gloss> defense. Although <persName corresp="#p_ASN1">Nuri</persName>
                    indicated this not presently possible, he intimated it might be in near
                    future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">McGhee</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
